@G[c3 stills_104.png]@L @H Historical Background @L Mediolanum, modern day Milan, was founded around 600 BC by the Insubrian peoples, a Celtic cultural group. Romans conquered the city in 222 BC, and it quickly became a local trade hub and major population center. By its conquest, Romans established a province of Gallia Cisalpina. @L@L Mediolanum was one of the most important cities in the Republic and later the Empire due to its location as a hub in the road network of northern Italy. Polybius describes the country as abounding in wine and every kind of grain and in fine wool. Herds of swine, both for public and private supply, were bred in its forests, and the people were well known for their generosity. @L@L Contrary to what is depicted in this scenario, the Mediolanum garrison did not in fact prevent the Carthaginian army from crossing the Alps, and Hannibal Barca continued to defeat one army after another while sacking small cities along the way. @L@L Ultimately, Hannibal's tactical victories did not turn into a strategic one and the Second Punic War ended in Rome's favor. @L@L
@G[c3 instructions icon.png] @H Instructions @L Governor, welcome to Mediolanum and its new province. Your task will be to transform this rugged northern landscape into a city worth its place as a provincial capital. @L@L Trade is limited to land caravans, but this should not pose a problem as there are plentiful Roman cities in close vicinity. There has also been talk of a trade pact amongst some of the eastern cities, so keep a close eye on the price of their trade permits, otherwise you might find yourself swiftly running out of available funds due to their extortionate practices. @L@L The local area is rich in marble, stone, and timber. Clay and sand can also be excavated with relative ease. Additionally, wheat can be grown; however, the northern climate does not suit the crop, and its yields are therefore low. Due to the rocky soils, the local land can support vegetables and vines as well. @L@L Speaking of trade, due to the ongoing conflict, weapons are demanded by almost every city. It is really a shame then that Mediolanum does not hold any deposits of iron ore. If you want to expand onto this profitable market or equip legionary cohorts, you will have to invest into imports of iron ore and manufacture weapons locally. @L@L Lastly, our surveyors told us that the site will be suitable for 8000 residents. This will no doubt rely on rapid expansion of food imports, but a governor skilled as you are will surely not fail in this endeavor. @L@L After talking about the economy, there are the matters of state and military. Our republic is locked in its great struggle against the Carthaginians for the second time in its history. Legions are few and far between in Italia and every city should care for its defense. Mediolanum will have the great barrier of the Alps between it and any potential danger, but your troops might be tasked with helping other cities. However, we do not expect any substantial force to trouble you and so cannot afford more than a small military presence in the region. @L@L Our legions must be tasked to defending the rest of the Republic; consequently, you will not build more than 2 legion forts in Mediolanum. Your city will also not have access to our military engineers and so will not be able to build towers or fortifications. Should matters change we will revisit this particular issue at a later date. @L@L One last note is that Pontifex Maximus, the chief priest of Rome, has decreed that no small shrine will be built; we must construct momentous constructions to the gods to foster religious zeal and dedication from all our citizens. He has forbidden the construction of small temples. He also sees the science of medicine as a distraction from the importance of pious worship; as such, you shall not construct any clinics. @L@L Good luck governor and remember your duties. We shall ask much of your fledgling city in the years to come. @L@L@L
@H Edicts @L@ Protected @by @the @Alps - You cannot build walls or towers until later events occur. If you build more than 2 forts, you will lose favor rapidly. @L@L@ Pontifical @Edict - You cannot build small temples or doctor's clinics. Swift construction of large temples or, better yet, oracles/mausolea will be necessary to avoid the wrath of the gods (your city starts with resources ready for use in warehouses). @L@L
@H Additional Information @L There are 8 invasion points; these are only on exposed edges of the map though, never on entry and exit points directly. Use chokepoints to wall one off and leave the other open as a kill zone so enemies path towards a single point of defense. @L@L At the time of the mission Rome is still in its republic stage, so treat requests from Caesar as if they were from the Roman Senate instead.@L@L As is customary, even though from a historical perspective you should start with a pre-built city on this map, few players would like that, so it will be up to you to build everything from scratch. @L @H Persistent Events @L Grand Temple to Mercury unlocks plaza. Subsidy lasts until 10 prosperity is achieved and gives 100 dn. monthly until it expires, workshops only unlock after subsidy expires. Due to game limitations, starting prices for goods will be adjusted after 1 in-game month has passed.@L@L@L@L

