		@H Historical Background @L
		During the crossing of the Alps, the Carthaginian army suffered unimaginable attrition but even after losing most of its strength, it was still capable of surprising the Romans and winning many battles. Their ranks were boosted by many local disgruntled Celtic tribesmen, eager to take revenge on the Romans for their past conquests. @L@L
		Hannibal Barca is regarded as one of the best generals in history, his tactical skill was unparalleled at the time and was in stark contrast to the rigid Roman way of fighting. He used ambushes and wide flanking maneuvers as well as hiding part of his forces to achieve surprise during battle. @L@L
		Romans suffered heavy defeats at Lake Trasimene and Cannae, even losing both consuls who led the armies. As with the Pyrrhic War in the past, the Roman war machine was very resilient, however. Even after tremendous losses, legions were rebuilt, tactics were improved, and enemies were overcome. @L@L
		Due to the lack of proper siege capabilities, the Carthaginians had to withdraw from Italy without achieving strategic victories and Hannibal later suffered his only defeat in the battle of Zama, when Scipio Africanus invaded North Africa. @L@L@L@L

